# S01-T01: React 19 + TypeScript + Vite + Full Stack Init

## Objective
Initialize the React 19 + TypeScript + Vite project in `/Projects/tactical-tablet-interface` with all core dependencies. Use navitrack's proven dependency versions where possible.

## Acceptance Criteria
- `npm create vite@latest . -- --template react-ts` executed
- React 19 installed (`react@^19`, `react-dom@^19`)
- Core dependencies:
  - `zustand@^5` — client state (navitrack version)
  - `@tanstack/react-query` — async state / transport cache
  - `react-router-dom@^7` — routing
  - `framer-motion@^12` — animations (navitrack version)
  - `tailwindcss@^3.4` + `postcss` + `autoprefixer` — styling (**Tailwind 3, NOT 4**)
  - `tailwindcss-animate` — animation utilities (navitrack uses this)
  - `clsx` + `tailwind-merge` — className utils (navitrack pattern)
  - `class-variance-authority` — variant components (navitrack pattern)
  - `lucide-react` — icons (navitrack uses this)
- DevDeps: `@types/react@^19`, `@types/react-dom@^19`
- `pnpm dev` starts successfully on port 1420
- `tsconfig.json`: strict mode, path aliases (`@/` → `src/`)
- `vite.config.ts`: port 1420, path aliases, dual-mode Tauri/web detection (navitrack pattern)
  - Separate caches: `.vite-tauri` vs `.vite-web`
  - Manual chunks for code splitting

## Why Tailwind 3 (not 4)
- navitrack ships to iOS/Android App Store with Tailwind 3 — production-proven
- `tailwind.config.ts` gives TypeScript control over theme
- Mature plugin ecosystem (`tailwindcss-animate`)
- HSL CSS variables → Tailwind config mapping is the proven pattern

## Steps
1. Initialize Vite project with react-ts template
2. Upgrade to React 19
3. Install all core dependencies (match navitrack versions)
4. Create `tailwind.config.ts`, `postcss.config.js`
5. Configure tsconfig paths and vite aliases
6. Setup dual-mode vite config (Tauri/web)
7. Verify build
